            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 1,
            AppRoutes = """["/invoices"]""",
            Tags = """["invoices","accounting","billing"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Invoices Overview\n\nThe Invoices module is how you bill your customers for finished work. Each invoice is a formal request for payment. It lists what you provided, the quantities and prices, the tax, and the total amount due.\n\n### Standalone vs Integrated Mode\n\nInvoices work one of two ways, depending on whether you've connected outside accounting software (like QuickBooks Online):\n\n- **Standalone mode** (nothing connected): You manage invoices right here — create, send, void, and delete them. This is how it works for shops that don't use separate accounting software.\n- **Integrated mode** (accounting software connected): Invoices become **view-only** here. They're pulled in from your accounting software for reference, and you manage them over there instead. A banner at the top of the page tells you which software is in charge.\n\nThe rest of this article covers standalone mode, where you're in full control.\n\n### Invoice Statuses\n\nEvery invoice moves through a few stages, shown by its status:\n\n- **Draft** — Created but not sent yet. You can send, void, or delete it. There's no editing a Draft in place — to change one, delete it and create a new one.\n- **Sent** — The invoice has gone to the customer. You can still void it, but you can no longer delete it.\n- **Partially Paid** — The customer has paid part of it. The balance due shows what's left.\n- **Paid** — Paid in full. The balance due is zero.\n- **Overdue** — The due date has passed and it isn't fully paid. The balance due shows in red.\n- **Voided** — Cancelled. Voided invoices stay on file for your records but don't affect any totals.\n\n### Line Items\n\nEach invoice has one or more line items. A line item is one thing you're billing for, with:\n- An optional **Part Number** that links the line to a part in your Parts Catalog\n- A **Description** of what you provided\n- A **Quantity** and a **Unit Price**\n- A **Line Total** worked out for you (quantity times unit price)\n\nThe **Subtotal** is all the line totals added up. **Tax** is the subtotal times your tax rate. The **Total** is subtotal plus tax. The **Balance Due** is the total minus whatever's been paid.\n\n### How Invoices Connect to Other Features\n\n**Sales Orders:** An invoice can be tied to a sales order. That links the billing back to the original customer order and lets you trace the whole path: Quote → Sales Order → Production → Shipment → Invoice → Payment.\n\n**Shipments:** An invoice can also point to a specific shipment. This is handy when a single order ships in several deliveries and you bill one at a time.\n\n**Payments:** As you record payments against an invoice, its amount paid goes up and its balance due goes down. Once it's fully paid, the status turns to Paid.\n\n**Jobs:** Finished jobs that haven't been billed show up in the Uninvoiced Jobs panel. You can build an invoice straight from a job, and it fills in the customer and line items for you.\n\n**Customers:** Every invoice belongs to a customer. The customer link on the invoice takes you to that customer's full profile.\n\n### Printing and Emailing\n\nInvoices can be saved as a PDF to email or print, complete with your company branding, line items, totals, and payment terms.\n\n### When to Use Invoices\n\n- After finishing a job and shipping goods to the customer\n- When billing for services you provided\n- When you need a formal payment request with line items and tax\n- To keep track of what's been paid and what's still owed\n- To keep a record of all your billing activity","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Walkthrough ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
