            Summary = "For the experienced office or AR clerk: billing in another currency, routing new invoices to one person, printing and emailing an invoice, picking up an unfinished invoice, and who can see the Invoices page.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Reference,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 90,
            AppRoutes = """["/invoices"]""",
            Tags = """["invoices","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Billing a customer in another currency\n\nMost shops bill everyone in one currency and never think about this. But if your business has set up more than one currency, an extra choice shows up when you build an invoice:\n\n- A **currency picker** appears on the invoice. Your home currency is chosen for you, so a one-currency shop never sees the picker at all.\n- When you pick a currency that isn't your home currency, an **exchange-rate box** appears. You enter the rate — how much one unit of that currency is worth in your home currency on the day you're billing.\n- Type the line prices in the currency you're billing in. The exchange rate is what lets your books convert the invoice back to your home currency.\n\nWhen in doubt, leave the currency alone: the default is always your home currency, and the rate box stays hidden.\n\n## Routing new invoices to one person\n\nA shop can bill one of two ways, and an admin sets which:\n\n- **Anyone bills directly** (the usual setup): whoever is on the Invoices page creates the invoice and it's done.\n- **One person owns billing**: new invoices land in a chosen person's queue instead of going out right away. Use this when you want a single accountant to review and send every invoice, so nothing goes to a customer without a second look.\n\nIf your shop routes invoices to one person, that's why a new invoice may not send the moment you build it — it's waiting for the billing owner. Ask your admin who that is.\n\n## Printing and emailing an invoice\n\nEvery invoice can become a clean PDF with your company's name, logo, line items, totals, and payment terms — the same document you'd mail or hand to a customer. Save it to print, or attach it to an email so the customer gets a professional-looking bill. Emailing the same invoice to the same address twice won't send two copies; the second one is recognized as a repeat and skipped, so a customer never gets doubled up.\n\n## Picking up an invoice you didn't finish\n\nIf you start an invoice and get pulled away — you log out, close the tab, or your browser refreshes — your work isn't lost. Forge quietly holds onto the half-finished invoice. Next time you open the Invoices page, it offers to reopen right where you left off so you can finish and save it.\n\n## Who can see and work with invoices\n\nInvoices are office work, not shop-floor work. Only office roles — an admin, a manager, or the office manager — can open the Invoices page and bill customers. Machinists, engineers, and other floor roles don't see invoices at all; they see the jobs, not the billing.\n\n## The accounting-software boundary, in plain terms\n\nHow much you can do here depends on whether your shop has connected outside accounting software like QuickBooks:\n\n- **No accounting software connected:** Forge is your billing system. You create, send, void, and delete invoices right here. Keep in mind a Draft can't be edited in place — to change one, delete it and build a new one. And you can only delete an invoice while it's still a Draft; once it's Sent, the record stays for your history and can only be voided.\n- **Accounting software connected:** your accounting software owns invoices. Forge hands your invoices over to it and shows them here for reference only — you'll do the actual billing over in QuickBooks. A banner at the top of the page tells you when this is the case.\n\nBills you owe to your vendors work the same way on the paying side of the house — the two mirror each other, one for money coming in and one for money going out.","sections":[]}"""
        });

